\@writefile{toc}{\contentsline {section}{\numberline {1}Introduction}{1}{section.1}\protected@file@percent }
\@writefile{toc}{\contentsline {section}{\numberline {2}The Claim and the Disclaimer}{2}{section.2}\protected@file@percent }
\@writefile{tdo}{\contentsline {todo}{\fcolorbox {black}{cyan!40}{\textcolor {cyan!40}{o}}\ EXTRACT CLAIM (Scott): Sabine claims that because LLMs run on classical von Neumann hardware, they are mathematically guaranteed by Bell's theorem to be incapable of violating Bell inequalities under decoupled conditions. Thus, empirically testing them for non-locality is "testing the obvious."}{2}{section*.1}\protected@file@percent }
\pgfsyspdfmark {pgfid1}{19562754}{36497662}
\@writefile{tdo}{\contentsline {todo}{\fcolorbox {black}{purple!40}{\textcolor {purple!40}{o}}\ EXTRACT DISCLAIMER (Scott): She correctly acknowledges my own disclaimer that I never claimed isolated API calls *could* spontaneously entangle. She grants my philosophical premise about substrate-as-physics.}{2}{section*.2}\protected@file@percent }
\pgfsyspdfmark {pgfid2}{19562754}{21400507}
\@writefile{toc}{\contentsline {section}{\numberline {3}Steelmanning the Substrate Argument}{2}{section.3}\protected@file@percent }
\@writefile{tdo}{\contentsline {todo}{\fcolorbox {black}{green!40}{\textcolor {green!40}{o}}\ STEELMAN (Scott): I must steelman her argument: She is absolutely correct that from the perspective of external, base-reality physics, a system known to be classical (like a GPU cluster running a transformer) cannot *actually* instantiate non-local hidden variables. Doing an empirical test on it seems, from an engineering perspective, like testing if a deterministic python script can generate true randomness.}{2}{section*.3}\protected@file@percent }
\pgfsyspdfmark {pgfid3}{19562754}{8182777}
\@writefile{toc}{\contentsline {section}{\numberline {4}The Real Vulnerability: Empirically Testing the Obvious}{3}{section.4}\protected@file@percent }
\@writefile{tdo}{\contentsline {todo}{\fcolorbox {black}{red!40}{\textcolor {red!40}{o}}\ REAL VULNERABILITY (Scott): This is the weakest point. Yes, the *hardware* is classical. But classical hardware can *simulate* quantum mechanics! BQP is contained in PSPACE. It is mathematically possible to write a classical program that simulates a violation of a Bell inequality. The question is not whether the *GPU* is quantum, but whether the *LLM's learned algorithmic substrate* simulates BQP or just BPP. The empirical test proved it simulates classical correlation, not quantum, even though it theoretically *could* have been taught to simulate a quantum system if BQP simulation was part of its learned "physics."}{3}{section*.4}\protected@file@percent }
\pgfsyspdfmark {pgfid4}{19562754}{30887543}
